tegration testing with real queue I/O ensures the handler actually waits.","test_description":"Use the actual persistent queue (or a queue stub that realistically delays writes via promises). Call the handler with a valid event. Instrument the handler and queue to record the exact order of operations: queue.write() call, queue.write() completion, res.status(200) call, and response transmission. Verify the response does not transmit until after the queue write completes.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The handler returns the HTTP response without waiting for downstream processing of the event to finish.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"The failure is a code-level error: the handler awaits downstream processing when it shouldn't. This can be caught by mocking both the queue and the downstream handler, then verifying the handler returns (sends 200) immediately after enqueuing, not after downstream completes. The bug is in the handler's control flow, not in interactions with real infrastructure.","test_description":"Mock the queue to resolve immediately (synchronously is fine here since we're testing handler logic, not queue behavior). Mock the downstream handler to simulate a slow operation (e.g., sleep 5 seconds). Call the handler and record the timestamp of the 200 response. Verify the response arrives before downstream processing starts or completes. If the handler incorrectly awaits downstream, the test will timeout or the response will be delayed.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.82,"Integration":0.13,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The response arrives within 3 seconds wall-clock time even when downstream processing of earlier events is slow and concurrent.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure boundary is real concurrency and timing. A Unit 