ption":"When the queue reports it is full, the handler returns 503 with a Retry-After header.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure is a missing error handler or incorrect response code/headers when the queue is at capacity. This must be tested against the real queue (or a queue with genuine capacity limits) to trigger the 'full' condition. A mock that always succeeds cannot expose missing error handling, and a mock that returns a generic error might miss the specific 503 + Retry-After requirement.","test_description":"Fill the persistent queue up to its configured capacity limit using real or integration-test writes. Send a new webhook request. Verify the handler catches the queue-full error, returns HTTP 503, includes a Retry-After header (with a reasonable value, e.g., 60 seconds), and does not enqueue the event.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.86,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"The persistent queue actually enforces its configured capacity limit and rejects events that would exceed it.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This test is not of the handler, but of the queue infrastructure itself. The queue is a separate subsystem (likely an external service like RabbitMQ, Redis, or a managed queue). To verify it enforces capacity, the test must interact with the real queue via its real API and attempt to exceed its limit. If the queue is a local in-process data structure, this could be Integration; if it's a subprocess or external service, it is System.","test_description":"Configure the queue with a known capacity limit (e.g., max 100 messages). Using the queue's real API (not through the handler), enqueue messages until capacity is reached. Attempt to enqueue one more message. Verify the queue rejects the message with an appropriate error (e.g., QUEUE_FULL). Confirm the rejection is consistent on retry. If capacity is soft (e.g., based on memory),